import React from 'react'; import './KbCite.css' const KbCite = () => { return(

Knowledge Base

Carbon free energy for Google Cloud regions

Google. (2021, March 15). Carbon free energy for Google cloud regions. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://cloud.google.com/sustainability/region-carbon

How clean is cloud computing? New data reveals how green Google's data centers really are

Leprince-Ringuet, D. (2021, March 17). How clean is cloud Computing? New data reveals how Green Google's data centers really are. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.zdnet.com/article/how-clean-is-cloud-computing-new-data-reveals-how-green-googles-data-centers-really-are/

When to use Marginal Emissions (and when not to)

Listgarten, S. (2019, September 29). When to use Marginal Emissions (and when not to). Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.paloaltoonline.com/blogs/p/2019/09/29/marginal-emissions-what-they-are-and-when-to-use-them

Average Emissions data

WattTime. (n.d.). Average Emissions data. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.citationmachine.net/bibliographies/df16e1f1-6da0-42c4-b408-2d91c4668b07

API Documentation

WattTime. (n.d.). Introduction. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.watttime.org/api-documentation/#introduction

Marginal emissions: what they are, and when to use them

Corradi, O. (2019, June 13). Marginal emissions: What they are, and when to use them. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.tmrow.com/blog/marginal-emissions-what-they-are-and-when-to-use-them/

How green is your cloud?

Mytton, I., & Mytton, D. (2015, December 16). How green is your cloud? Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.infoworld.com/article/3015632/how-green-is-your-cloud.html

Microsoft Joins RE100 Initiative In Support of Renewable Energy

Bernard, R. (2016, December 14). Microsoft joins RE100 initiative in support of renewable energy. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://blogs.microsoft.com/green/2015/11/30/microsoft-joins-re100-initiative-in-support-of-renewable-energy/

The Carbon Benefits of Cloud Computing

Microsoft. (n.d.). The carbon benefits of cloud computing Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/confirmation.aspx?id=56950

Reducing the Carbon Emissions of ML Computing

EEMS Group (Director). (2020, July 29). Reducing the carbon emissions of ML computing - challenges and opportunities [Video file]. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vrc1H4xSH7o

Green AI

Schwartz, R., Dodge, J., Smith, N., & Etzioni, O. (2019, July). Green AI. Retrieved March 28, 2021, from https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.10597.pdf

Carbontracker: Tracking and Predicting the Carbon Footprint of Training Deep Learning Models

Anthony, L. W., Kanding, B., & Selvan, R. (2020, July 6). Carbontracker: Tracking and Predicting the Carbon Footprint of Training Deep Learning Models. Retrieved March 28, 2021, from https://arxiv.org/pdf/2007.03051.pdf

Energy and Policy Considerations for Deep Learning in NLP

Strubell, Emma, Ganesh, Ananya, & McCallum, Andrew. (2019). Energy and Policy Considerations for Deep Learning in NLP. Retrieved March 28, 2021, from https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.02243

The Cost of Training NLP Models: A Concise Overview

Sharir, Or, Peleg, Barak, & Shoham, Yoav. (2020). The Cost of Training NLP Models: A Concise Overview. Retrieved March 28, 2021, from https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.08900

API development for everyone

Swagger. (n.d.). API development for everyone. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://swagger.io/

Welcome to Flask

Flask. (n.d.). Welcome to flask. Retrieved March 29, 2021, from https://flask-doc.readthedocs.io/en/latest/

The Climate Pledge

Amazon. (n.d.). The climate pledge. Retrieved April 01, 2021, from https://sustainability.aboutamazon.com/about/the-climate-pledge

Environmental sustainability: Microsoft CSR

Microsoft. (n.d.). Environmental sustainability: Microsoft CSR. Retrieved April 01, 2021, from https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/corporate-responsibility/sustainability?activetab=pivot_1%3Aprimaryr3

Microsoft Will Be Carbon Negative by 2030

Smith, B. (n.d.). Microsoft Will Be Carbon Negative by 2030 [Web log post]. Retrieved April 01, 2021, from https://aka.ms/MSFTcarbonfactsheet


); } export default KbCite;
